<font color="#FF0000">A CONTRARYS CODE OF CONDUCT</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec  9  1:40:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
An Anonymous contrary that sounds ALL too familiar is posting again. Below is the Contrary’s Code of Conduct. This will allow Vietnam Veterans to better understand why they post as they do and we will be able to have real dialog with contrarys by using their terms and misunderstandings.<br><br>
A CONTRARYS CODE OF CONDUCT<br><br>
1. As I let go of my feelings of guilt, I can get in touch with my Inner Sociopath. <br>
2. I have the power to channel my imagination into ever-soaring levels of suspicion and paranoia.<br>
3. I assume full responsibility for my actions, except the ones that are someone else's fault. <br>
4. I no longer need to punish, deceive or compromise myself. Unless, of course, I want to stay employed.<br>
5. Having control over myself is nearly as good as having control over others. <br>
6. My intuition nearly makes up for my lack of good judgment.<br>
7. I can change any thought that hurts into a reality that hurts even more.<br>
8. I honor my personality flaws, for without them I would have no personality at all.<br>
9. I am grateful that I am not as judgmental as all those censorious, self-righteous people around me.<br>
10. I need not suffer in silence while I can still moan, whimper and complain.<br>
11. As I learn the innermost secrets of the people around me, they reward me in many ways to keep me quiet.<br>
12. When someone hurts me, forgiveness is cheaper than a lawsuit. But not nearly as gratifying.<br>
13. The first step is to say nice things about myself. The second, to do nice things for myself. The third, to find someone to say nice things about me.<br>
14. All of me is beautiful and valuable, even the ugly, stupid, and disgusting parts.<br>
15. I am at one with my duality.<br>
16. Only a lack of imagination saves me from immobilizing myself with imaginary fears.<br>
17. Does my quiet self-pity get to me? Yes? Or should I move up to incessant nagging?<br>
18. I honor and express all facets of my being, regardless of state and local laws.<br>
19. A good scapegoat is nearly as welcome as a solution to the problem.<br>
20. Who can I blame for my own problems? Give me just a minute...I'll find someone.<br>
21. I am learning that criticism is not nearly as effective as sabotage.<br>
22. Becoming aware of my character defects leads me to the next step-blaming my parents.<br>
23. I will find humor in my everyday life by looking for people I can laugh at.<br>
24. I am willing to make the mistakes if someone else is willing to learn from them.<br><br>
Submitted as obtained with only slight modifications made to protect the guilty from their own arrogance.<br><br>
Cook Barela<br>

<p><code>--   (Anonymous) </code><p>


